  "notes": "Sitemap path was a dead end: the McKinsey main sitemap.xml is a single ~1MB+ XML file delivered as one logical line, truncated at 1MB by web_fetch and unsearchable by ripgrep due to line length. robots.txt confirms only one sitemap exists (no sub-sitemap index). Workspace bash has no outbound internet access, so curl-based slicing was not possible. Pivoted entirely to LEAD 2 (WebSearch with site: queries). Ran ~14 diversified queries across topical (AI, healthcare, energy, productivity, banking, mobility, retail, geopolitics, workforce, climate, trade, semiconductors, pharma) and temporal (Nov 2025, Dec 2025, Jan-Apr 2026, individual months) angles, deduplicating across results. Captured 40 unique URLs after dedupe; filtered to 40 entries dated Nov 1 2025 onward (one entry, 'opportunity-in-trade-uncertainty', has an inferred Dec 2025 date based on context but was not explicitly dated in search results; 'trade-turmoil-takes-hold' has unknown date and may pre-date Nov 2025 — flagged with null). Note: McKinsey publishes Week in Charts every Saturday with ~5-6 individual chart entries per issue, but each chart URL discovered above is the canonical page for one individual chart entry (not the issue index). Total of 40 entries here vs the user's expectation of 120-150 means WebSearch likely missed a substantial portion (Google search APIs cap at ~10 results per query). To approach 150 entries, a follow-on step should fetch one of these chart pages to find 'related charts' or 'this week's charts' link blocks that point to the other 4-5 charts in the same issue, OR use the McKinsey GraphQL/Sitecore API if discoverable. Search-result dates are best-effort: McKinsey labels each chart with its individual publication date which may differ by 1-2 days from the Saturday issue date. 25 issues x ~6 charts = ~150 expected; we have ~40, so coverage is ~25-30%. This is the practical ceiling for WebSearch-only enumeration."
